    <text id="R1469640T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Union Colonel Sharpe writes J. C. Babcock in January, 1865, regarding Confederate
                    troop positions. He reports General Jubal Early is at Staunton.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    OFFICE OF THE PROVOST-MARSHAL-GEN.,<lb/> ARMIES OPERATING AGAINST RICHMOND
                    <name type="recipient">J. C. BABCOCK,<lb/> Hdqrs. Army of the Potomac:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1865-01-05">January 5, 1865.</date>
                        <name type="place">City Point</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute/>
                </opener>
                <p>I have deserters to-day from Pickett's division and from the Local Defense Troops
                    on the north side. There is no change in Pickett's brigades, nor, as far as I
                    can judge, on the north side, where Field holds the line next the river; then
                    the Local Defense Troops or city battalions and the reserves, all commanded by
                    G. W. Custis Lee, and Kershaw toward the Darbytown road. I hear nothing of
                    Hoke's return. Our news from Washington is that Early is at Staunton.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute/>
                    <signed>SHARPE,<lb/> Col.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
